Interpretation of Sensitivity Analysis Results:

I conducted a sensitivity analysis on the estimated uplift between Variant 2 and Variant 1's conversion rates using a Bayesian Beta-Binomial model. The goal was to assess how different prior beliefs affect our posterior conclusions.

1. Technical Interpretation

Each row represents the result of running the same Bayesian model with a different Beta prior on the conversion rates:

Prior Parameters Interpretation
Uniform (1,1) Beta(1, 1) Assumes all conversion rates between 0 and 1 are equally likely (non-informative).
Skeptical (3,17) Beta(3, 17) Encodes belief that conversion is around 15%, but with moderate uncertainty.
Weakly informative (15,85) Beta(15, 85) Encodes stronger belief centered at 15%, based on expected historical patterns.
Historical (150,850) Beta(150, 850) Strong prior centered at 15% using historical data from similar tests (tight concentration).

Posterior Uplift Statistics (Variant B vs. Variant A):

  • All priors lead to slightly negative mean uplift estimates (~-1.5%).
  • 95% credible intervals all span 0, indicating that the uplift is not credibly different from zero under any prior.
  • The probability that uplift is positive ( P(uplift > 0) ) ranges between 17.15% and 18.03%, consistently low across priors.

This indicates that the posterior is largely robust to the prior choice in this case, likely due to the moderate-to-large sample size (~41K users per group).

2. Business Interpretation

  • No meaningful uplift: Under all assumptions, Variant 2 shows a slightly lower conversion rate than Variant 1. The posterior probability that 2 outperforms 1 is less than 20%, far below any reasonable decision threshold (e.g. 95%).
  • Stable conclusion: This conclusion holds across different prior beliefs, including skeptical, historical, and agnostic stances.

3. Actionable Business Recommendations

  • Do not ship Variant 2: Based on conversion and revenue metrics, there is no evidence of improvement and some evidence of degradation.
  • Default to Variant 1: It remains the better-performing baseline in terms of both conversion and monetization.
  • Explore qualitative feedback: Since Variant 2 included both pricing and offer reductions, we need to gather user insights or segment-level data to understand the demand function better.
  • Consider segment-level analysis next: If there's a business hypothesis that certain user groups (e.g., new users, mobile-only) respond better to 2, a hierarchical or stratified model may uncover hidden effects.
  • Use historical data to design stronger priors in future experiments, especially if sample sizes are smaller or more noise-prone.

In summary, the Bayesian analysis provides strong, interpretable, and stable evidence that Variant 1 should remain the default offer in the current business context.
